<h1>Cross-cutting observations</h1>

<p>The three deep threads converge on one arc. <b>State is the binding constraint on world(-action) models, and the field is starting to pay it down.</b> Pixels-to-States documents the debt: six of six recent models keep state implicit, and persistence mechanisms are either past-copies or ungrounded latents. BadWAM prices a piece of the debt: implicit coupling between imagination and action is not a safety feature — it is a monitorable-looking surface that can be driven apart along a measurable frontier, with a geometric ceiling set by shared low-rank input sensitivity. RoboTTT shows one repayment plan: carry the state in fast weights with a self-supervised inner objective, train long-context, and you get flat-latency memory plus in-context adaptation — at the cost of stability guarantees that currently come from training rather than structure.</p>

<p>The open question this run leaves on the table: <b>can a carried state be made both explicit and learned?</b> Kairos's recurrent matrix is carried but opaque; the game-engine lens wants explicit and rule-governed; RoboTTT's fast weights are learned and self-updating but inspectable only by probe. A WAM whose carried state is a structured, queryable object — HP bars for robots, effectively — would satisfy all three papers at once, and the Pixels-to-States data engine (engine-exported states, frame-aligned) is exactly the supervision such a model would need. That is the buildable idea we would pursue next.</p>

<p><b>Run notes.</b> MinerU's API token expired mid-run (401); papers were read via arXiv HTML full text instead, with no loss of depth. All probes are preserved in the run packet: the toy WAM + BadWAM attack suite (numpy, reproducible in minutes), the TTT/delta/attention context-scaling probe with trained checkpoints, and the six-model state taxonomy with quoted evidence.</p>
